Plane EM Wave - Dr. Ray Kwok

Plane Wave
\[
\begin{array}{l}
\nabla^{2} \overrightarrow{\mathrm{E}}=\mu \varepsilon \frac{\partial^{2} \overrightarrow{\mathrm{E}}}{\partial \mathrm{t}^{2}} \\
\overrightarrow{\mathrm{E}}(\overrightarrow{\mathrm{r}}, \mathrm{t})=\overrightarrow{\mathrm{E}}_{\mathrm{o}} \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{j}(\omega t-\overrightarrow{-} \cdot \vec{r})} \\
\nabla^{2} \overrightarrow{\mathrm{E}}=-\mathrm{k}^{2} \overrightarrow{\mathrm{E}} \\
\frac{\partial^{2} \overrightarrow{\mathrm{E}}}{\partial \mathrm{t}^{2}}=-\omega^{2} \overrightarrow{\mathrm{E}} \\
-\mathrm{k}^{2}=-\omega^{2} \mu \varepsilon \\
\mathrm{k}=\omega \sqrt{\mu \varepsilon} \\
\frac{\omega}{\mathrm{k}}=\mathrm{v}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\mu \varepsilon}}
\end{array}
\]

Similarly for B or H field
\[
\begin{array}{l}
\nabla^{2} \overrightarrow{\mathrm{H}}=\mu \varepsilon \frac{\partial^{2} \overrightarrow{\mathrm{H}}}{\partial \mathrm{t}^{2}} \\
\overrightarrow{\mathrm{H}}(\overrightarrow{\mathrm{r}}, \mathrm{t})=\overrightarrow{\mathrm{H}}_{\mathrm{o}} \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{j}(\omega t-\overrightarrow{\mathrm{k}} \cdot \overrightarrow{\mathrm{r}}}
\end{array}
\]

