Source-free EM wave
\( \overrightarrow{\mathrm{E}}(\overrightarrow{\mathrm{r}}, \mathrm{t})=\hat{\mathrm{x}} \mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{o}} \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{j}(\omega t-\mathrm{kz})} \quad \mathrm{V} / \mathrm{m} \) in vacuum with no current source.

What is \( \mathbf{H} \) ?
\[
\begin{array}{l}
\nabla \times \overrightarrow{\mathrm{E}}=\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
\hat{\mathrm{x}} & \hat{\mathrm{y}} & \hat{\mathrm{z}} \\
\frac{\partial}{\partial \mathrm{x}} & \frac{\partial}{\partial \mathrm{y}} & \frac{\partial}{\partial \mathrm{z}} \\
\mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{o}} \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{j}(\omega t-\mathrm{kz})} & 0 & 0
\end{array}\right| \\
\nabla \times \overrightarrow{\mathrm{E}}=-\mathrm{j} \omega \mu \mathrm{H} \\
\nabla \times \overrightarrow{\mathrm{E}}=\hat{\mathrm{y}}\left\{-\mathrm{jkE} \mathrm{o}_{\mathrm{o}}^{\mathrm{j}(\omega t-\mathrm{kz})}\right\} \\
\overrightarrow{\mathrm{H}}(\overrightarrow{\mathrm{r}}, \mathrm{t})=\hat{\mathrm{y}} \frac{\mathrm{kE}_{\mathrm{o}}}{\omega \mu} \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{j}(\omega t-\mathrm{kz})}
\end{array}
\]
\[
\begin{array}{l}
\nabla \times \vec{E}=\hat{y}\left\{-j k E_{o} e^{j(\omega t-k z)}\right\} \\
\vec{H}(\vec{r}, t)=\hat{y} \frac{k E_{o}}{\omega \mu} e^{j(\omega t-k z)} \\
\frac{k}{\omega \mu}=\frac{1}{f \lambda \mu}=\frac{1}{v \mu}=\frac{\sqrt{\mu \varepsilon}}{\mu}=\sqrt{\frac{\varepsilon}{\mu}} \equiv \frac{1}{\eta} \\
\vec{H}(\vec{r}, t)=\hat{y} \frac{E_{o}}{\eta} e^{j(\omega t-k z)} \quad \begin{array}{c}
\eta=\text { wave } \\
\text { Impedance }
\end{array} \\
\vec{B}=\mu \vec{H}=\hat{y} \frac{\mu E_{o}}{v \mu} e^{j(\omega t-k z)} \\
\vec{B}(\vec{r}, t)=\hat{y} \frac{E_{o}}{v} e^{j(\omega t-k z)}
\end{array}
\]

