Dr. Ray Kwok, SJSU

Here is another confusion that often comes up in the first solution.
I worte, for the normal component,
\[
\begin{array}{l}
B_{1 n}=\vec{B}_{1} \cdot \hat{n}_{2} \\
B_{2 n}=\vec{B}_{2} \cdot \hat{n}_{2}
\end{array}
\]

Why did I use the same normal vector? Why not...
\[
\begin{array}{l}
B_{1 n}=\vec{B}_{1} \cdot \hat{n}_{1} \\
B_{2 n}=\vec{B}_{2} \cdot \hat{n}_{2}
\end{array}
\]

To understand this, we need to go back to the definition of the bourndary conditions, and understand how we derived it, and what does it mean?

Anyway to see it is to explicitly write the B field in terms of normal and tangential components. This is the \( 3^{\text {rd }} \) way to solve the problem in the following pages.

