Electrostatic - Dr. Ray Kwok
\[
\rho=\alpha z^{2}
\]
use a solid disc as a building block
\[
\begin{array}{l}
M=\int_{-R}^{R}\left(\alpha z^{2}\right)\left(\pi r^{2} d z\right) \\
M=2 \alpha \pi \int_{0}^{R} z^{2}\left(R^{2}-z^{2}\right) d z=2 \alpha \pi\left(\frac{R^{5}}{3}-\frac{R^{5}}{5}\right) \\
M=\frac{4}{15} \alpha \pi R^{5}
\end{array}
\]

To find the current density on the ground plane (xy-plane), we need to find the B-field right above it. i.e., \( \vec{B}_{\text {total }}\left(z=0^{+}\right)= \)?
\[
\begin{array}{l}
\vec{B}_{\text {total }}\left(z \rightarrow 0^{+}\right) \\
=\frac{\mu_{o} I}{2 \pi\left[v^{2}+(x-u)^{2}\right]}\langle v, 0, x-u\rangle+\frac{\mu_{o} I}{2 \pi\left[v^{2}+(x+u)^{2}\right]}\langle-v, 0,-(x+u)\rangle \\
\quad+\frac{\mu_{o} I}{2 \pi\left[v^{2}+(x-u)^{2}\right]}\langle v, 0,-(x-u)\rangle+\frac{\mu_{o} I}{2 \pi\left[v^{2}+(x+u)^{2}\right]}\langle-v, 0, x+u\rangle \\
=\frac{\mu_{o} I}{2 \pi\left[v^{2}+(x-u)^{2}\right]}\langle 2 v, 0,0\rangle+\frac{\mu_{o} I}{2 \pi\left[v^{2}+(x+u)^{2}\right]}\langle-2 v, 0,0\rangle \\
=\hat{x} \frac{\mu_{o} I v}{\pi}\left\{\frac{1}{v^{2}+(x-u)^{2}}-\frac{1}{v^{2}+(x+u)^{2}}\right\} \\
=\hat{x} \frac{\mu_{o} I v}{\pi}\left\{\frac{4 x u}{\left[v^{2}+(x-u)^{2}\right]\left[v^{2}+(x+u)^{2}\right]}\right\}
\end{array}
\]

Note: B-field just above the ground plane is only in the \( x \)-direction. It MUST be tangential to the surface. WHY???

Now apply the boundary condition:
\[
\begin{array}{l}
\vec{J}_{s}=\hat{n}_{2} \times\left(\vec{H}_{1}-\vec{H}_{2}\right)=\hat{z} \times\left(\hat{x} \frac{4 I v u x}{\pi\left[v^{2}+(x-u)^{2}\right]\left[v^{2}+(x+u)^{2}\right]}-0\right) \\
\vec{J}_{s}=\hat{y} \frac{4 I v u x}{\pi\left[v^{2}+(x-u)^{2}\right]\left[v^{2}+(x+u)^{2}\right]}
\end{array}
\]

This is, of course, for \( \mathrm{x}>0 \) only. Note also the image current is in the y direction (into the page), while the real current on the wire is coming out of the page, as expected.

